<HEADLINE>
Russia mulls to reinforce enclave troops against U.S. missile
shield
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, Jan. 30 (Xinhua)
</P>
<P>
Russia is considering to reconfigure troops in its enclaved
territory of Kaliningrad region in a bid to cope with United
States' planned anti-ballistic missile components in East Europe,
a senior officer said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reinforced troops "would be capable of guarantied fulfillment
of the task to protect Russian interests," Itar-Tass news agency
quoted chief of the Combat Training Department of the Russian
armed forces Vladimir Shamanov as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The General Staff, together with the Combat Training Department,
is considering and deciding on the way we'll configure the group
of troops in this region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kaliningrad, surrounded by Poland and Lithuania, currently hosts
Russia's Baltic Fleet headquarters, a marines brigade, a missile
brigade and two motorized infantry brigades, and several Air
Force and air defense units.
</P>
<P>
Washington plans to deploy interceptor missiles in Poland and a
radar station in the Czech Republic, which is facing fierce
opposition from Moscow.
</P>
